\f[CR]del\f[R]
.SH TYPICAL WORKFLOW
Initial setup:
.IP
.EX
tildr init
tildr add .bashrc
tildr add .config/nvim
tildr status
tildr apply
tildr sync
.EE
.PP
Recovery and maintenance:
.IP
.EX
tildr status
tildr doctor
tildr apply
tildr unlink .config/nvim
tildr restore .bashrc
.EE
.SH OPERATIONAL NOTES
.IP \[bu] 2
Tildr is designed for home\-directory management on Linux and macOS
.IP \[bu] 2
The repository must stay inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Relative paths for managed targets are interpreted from \f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Directory operations are recursive over all files under that path
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]apply\f[R] does not overwrite conflicting regular files unless
\f[CR]\-\-force\f[R] is provided
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]unlink\f[R] removes only symlinks, never repository content
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]restore\f[R] physically moves the real file back out of the
repository
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]del\f[R] removes repository content; use \f[CR]\-\-purge\f[R] for
permanent deletion
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]git.auto_commit\f[R] affects \f[CR]add\f[R], \f[CR]restore\f[R],
and \f[CR]del\f[R] \[em] not \f[CR]apply\f[R], \f[CR]unlink\f[R],
\f[CR]git\f[R], or \f[CR]sync\f[R]
